A type class for functors that support application, i.e. allow to:
- Make an applicative value out of a normal value (embed it into a default context), e.g. embed `5` into `Some(5)`.
- Apply a function-type applicative to a matching argument-type applicative, resulting in an applicative of
the function's result type.
The meaning of the application realized by the `ap` function is defined by the respective instance.
Conceptually this can be understood as applying functions "contained" in the first applicative to arguments
in the second applicative, where the possible quantity of functions/arguments depends on the type `m`.
For example, an `Option[a -> b]` can be `None`, or contain a function of type `a -> b`, and only in the
latter case a function is applied. A `List[a -> b]` is an applicative that contains a list of functions,
which are all to be applied to all arguments contained in the arguments list.
A minimal implementation must define `point` and at least one of `ap` and `map2` (if `map2` is implemented,
`ap` can be defined based on `map2` as shown below). If both `ap` and `map2` are defined,
they must be equivalent to their default definitions:
`ap(f: m[a -> b \ e], x: m[a]): m[b] \ ef = map2(identity, f, x)`
`map2(f: a -> b -> c \ e, x: m[a], y: m[b]): m[c] \ ef = ap(Functor.map(f, x), y)`

A red-black tree is a self-balancing binary search tree.
Each node is either red or black, although a transitory
color double-black is allowed during deletion.
The red-black tree satisfy the following invariants.
1. For all nodes with key `x`,
the left subtree contains only nodes with keys `y` < `x` and
the right subtree contains only nodes with keys `z` > `x`.
2. No red node has a red parent.
3. Every path from the root to a leaf contains the same
number of black nodes.

* `ReqArg` mandates an argument. The constructor takes a function to decode the argument and description string.

failure.

* `RequireOrder` after the first non-option all remain arguments are treated as non-options

That is, returns `b1 :: a1 ... an :: b2 :: ... bn-1 :: a1 :: ... :: an :: bn :: Nil`.
Does *not* consume any elements from either iterator.
The original iterators `sep` and `iter` should not be reused.
Iterator.name: intercalate

doc: Returns an iterator with `a` inserted between every of `iter`.
Does *not* consume any elements from the iterator.
Iterator.name: intersperse

doc: Returns an iterator built with the stepper function `f`.
Iterator.name: iterate

doc: Returns the concatenation of the string representation
of each element in `iter` with `sep` inserted between each element.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: join

doc: Returns the concatenation of the string representation
of each element in `iter` according to `f` with `sep` inserted between each element.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: joinWith

doc: Returns an iterator with every `f` lazily applied to each element in `iter`.
Does *not* consume any elements from the iterator.
Iterator.name: map

doc: Returns an iterator with every `f` lazily applied to each element in `iter`
together with its index.
Does *not* consume any elements from the iterator.
Iterator.name: mapWithIndex

doc: Returns `Some(x)` if `iter` is not empty. Returns `None` otherwise.
Consumes the head element of `iter`.
Iterator.name: next

doc: Returns an iterator of all integers between `b` (inclusive) and `e` (exclusive).
Returns an empty iterator if `b >= e`.
Iterator.name: range

doc: Applies `f` to all elements in `iter` going from left to right until a single value `v` is obtained.  Returns `Some(v)`.
That is, the result is of the form: `Some(f(...f(f(x1, x2), x3)..., xn))`
Returns `None` if `iter` is empty.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: reduceLeft

doc: Returns an iterator over an iterable with the element `x` repeated `n` times.
Returns an empty iterator if `n < 0`.
Iterator.name: repeat

doc: Returns an iterator with every occurrence of `from` replaced by `to` in `iter`.
Does *not* consume any elements from the iterator.
Iterator.name: replace

doc: Returns an iterator containing only a single element, `x`.
Iterator.name: singleton

doc: Returns the sum of all elements in the iterator `iter`.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: sum

doc: Returns the sum of all elements in the iterator `iter` according to the function `f`.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: sumWith

doc: Returns `iter` with the first `n` elements.
Returns `iter` if `n` is larger than the number of elements in `iter`.
Returns an empty iterator if `n < 0`.
Does *not* consume any elements from the iterator.
The original iterator `iter` should *not* be reused.
Iterator.name: take

doc: Returns the longest prefix of `iter` that satisfies the predicate `f`.
Does *not* consume any elements from the iterator.
The original iterator `iter` should *not* be reused.
Iterator.name: takeWhile

doc: Returns the contents of `iter` as an array.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: toArray

doc: Returns the contents of `iter` as a chain.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: toChain

doc: Returns the contents of `iter` as a list.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: toList

doc: Returns the contents of `iter` as a map.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: toMap

doc: Returns the contents of `iter` as a MutDeque.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: toMutDeque

doc: Returns the contents of `iter` as a Nec.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: toNec

doc: Returns the contents of `iter` as a `Some(Nel)` if `iter` is not empty. Returns None otherwise.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: toNel

doc: Returns the contents of `iter` as a set. Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: toSet

doc: Returns the contents of `iter` as an array.
Consumes the entire iterator.
Iterator.name: toVector

doc: Returns an iterator over the results of `f`.
If `f` returns `Ok(x)`, then the next element is `x`.
If `f` returns `Err(e)`, then the iterator is depleted.
Iterator.name: unfoldWithOk

doc: Returns an iterator where the element at index `i` is `(a, b)` where
`a` is the element at index `i` in `iterA` and `b` is the element at index `i` in `iterB`.
Does *not* consume any elements from either iterator.
If either `iterA` or `iterB` is depleted, then no further elements are added to the resulting iterator.
The original iterators `iterA` and `iterB` should *not* be reused.
An iterator should *never* be zipped with itself.
Iterator.name: zip
Iterator.tpe: Iterator[(a, b), r2 + ef1 + ef2, r1]

doc: Returns an iterator where the element at index `i` is `f(a, b)` where
`a` is the element at index `i` in `iterA` and `b` is the element at index `i` in `iterB`.
Does *not* consume any elements from either iterator.
If either `iterA` or `iterB` becomes depleted, then no further elements are added to the resulting list.
The original iterators `iterA` and `iterB` should *not* be reused.
An iterator should *never* be zipped with itself.
Iterator.name: zipWith
Iterator.tpe: Iterator[c, ef3 + ef1 + ef2 + r2, r1]

doc: Returns an iterator where the element at index `i` is `(a, i)` where
`a` is the element at index `i` in `iter`.
Does *not* consume any elements from the iterator.
The original iterator `iter` should *not* be reused.
Iterator.name: zipWithIndex

doc: Decode the list of command line options supplied to the program.
`ordering` mandates how processing of options and non-options is handled.
`optDescriptors` is a list of processors for decoding individual options.
`sourceArgs` should be the list of command line arguments supplied to the program.
If successful, `getOpt` returns lists of decoded options and non-options. If unsuccessful it
returns a non-empty list of error messages, with unknown options considered to be errors.
GetOpt.name: getOpt

doc: This is a more general version of `getOpt` that returns all the results of decoding the command line
options without distinguishing whether the decoding is successful or a failure.
Client code calling this function, rather than `getOpt`, is free to process or ignore the results collected
in `unknowns` and `errors` which would indicate problems with the decoding if either were not empty.
GetOpt.name: getOpt1
GetOpt.tpe: { errors = List[String], nonOptions = List[String], options = List[a], unknowns = List[String] }

doc: Preprocess the command line arguments before parsing them.
Arguments supplied as an `List[String]` to the program are simply derived from the input split on space.
This does not account for, for example, Windows file names which may include space.
`preprocess` is a simple function that can be used to "rejoin" command line arguments if they were
joined by "quotation marks" in the user supplied string (quotations marks are configurable and do not
have to be double quotes).
GetOpt.name: preprocess

fparams.name: options
fparams.tpe: { quoteClose = String, quoteOpen = String, stripQuoteMarks = Bool }

doc: Return a formatted string describing the usage of the command.
Typically this output is used by "--help"
GetOpt.name: usageInfo

doc: Returns the number of Chars needed to represent the code point `cp`.
The answer is either 2 for a supplementary character or 1 for any other character.
CodePoint.name: charCount

doc: Returns the name of the code point `cp`.
See the Java JDK documentation of the method `java.lang.Character.getName` for a full
description of how names are derived.
CodePoint.name: getName

doc: Returns the integer value representated by the code point `cp` e.g. code point 0x0031
which is the char '1' returns `Some(1)`.
Returns `None` if `cp` does not represent a number.
This function handles supplementary characters.
CodePoint.name: getNumericValue

doc: Optionally returns the high surrogate character of the code point `cp`
if `cp` is a supplementary character.
CodePoint.name: highSurrogate

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents an alphabetic character.
CodePoint.name: isAlphabetic

doc: Returns `true` if the given char `c` is an ascii character.
CodePoint.name: isAscii

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents a character strictly in the
range of ASCII digits 0...9.
CodePoint.name: isAsciiDigit

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` is within Unicode's Basic Multilingual Plane.
If the code point is within the BMP it can be represented by Flix's `Char` datatype.
CodePoint.name: isBmpCodePoint

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` is defined either as a entry in the
UnicodeData file or a value within a range defined in the UnicodeData file.
CodePoint.name: isDefined

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents a recognized Unicode digit.
This includes the ASCII range 0..9 but also Arabic-Indic digits, Devagari digits and Fullwidth digits.
CodePoint.name: isDigit

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents a character in the range 0...F.
CodePoint.name: isHexDigit

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` is an ISO control character.
CodePoint.name: isISOControl

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` is Chinese, Japanase, Korean
or Vietnamese ideograph.
CodePoint.name: isIdeographic

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents a letter character.
CodePoint.name: isLetter

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents a recognized Unicode letter or digit.
CodePoint.name: isLetterOrDigit

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents a lowercase letter.
CodePoint.name: isLowerCase

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` is mirrored.
CodePoint.name: isMirrored

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents a character in the range 0...7.
CodePoint.name: isOctDigit

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` is in Unicode's supplementary character range.
CodePoint.name: isSupplementaryCodePoint

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents a titlecase letter.
CodePoint.name: isTitleCase

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents an uppercase letter.
CodePoint.name: isUpperCase

doc: Returns `true` if the code point `cp` is between `U+0000` and `U+10FFFF`.
CodePoint.name: isValidCodePoint

doc: Returns `true` if the given code point `cp` represents a white space character.
CodePoint.name: isWhiteSpace

doc: Optionally returns the low surrogate character of the code point `cp`
if `cp` is a supplementary character.
CodePoint.name: lowSurrogate

doc: Returns the maximum integer value of a Unicode code point.
CodePoint.name: maxValue

doc: Returns the minimum integer value of a Unicode code point.
CodePoint.name: minValue

doc: Optionally returns a Char represention the code point `cp` if `cp` is within
Unicode's Basic Multilingual Plane.
CodePoint.name: toBmpChar

doc: Optionally returns a vector of Chars representing the code point `cp`.
A valid `Some(_)` answer is either a length 2 Vector for a supplementary character
or a length 1 Vector for any other valid character.
Returns 'None' if `cp` is not a valid code point.
CodePoint.name: toChars

doc: Converts a code point representing a letter to its lowercase version.
Returns the original code point if it does not have a lowercase version.
CodePoint.name: toLowerCase

doc: Returns a String representing the code point `cp`.
CodePoint.name: toString

doc: Optionally returns a pair of Chars representing the high and low surrogate characters of the
code point `cp` if `cp` is a supplementary character.
CodePoint.name: toSupplementaryChars

doc: Converts a code point representing a letter to its titlecase version.
Returns the original character if it does not have either a titlecase
version or a mapping to uppercase.
CodePoint.name: toTitleCase

doc: Converts a code point representing a letter to its uppercase version.
Returns the original code point if it does not have a uppercase version.
CodePoint.name: toUpperCase

doc: Returns the shortest distance between all pairs of nodes in the
weighted directed graph `g`.
OBS: No negative cycles must be present.
Graph.name: boundedDistances

doc: Returns the pairs `(a, b)` where `a` can reach `b` through a number of
edges in the directed graph `g`, including zero.
Graph.name: closure

doc: Returns triples `(x, cut, y)` such that `x` cannot reach `y` without
using `cut` (where `x`, `cut` and `y` are all distinct) in the directed
graph `g`.
There will at most be one triple for each pair of nodes (which will
be the maximum `cut` of the possible choices).
Graph.name: cutPoints

doc: Returns the degree of each node in the directed graph `g` (the number of
times a node exists as an endpoint of an edge).
Graph.name: degrees

doc: Returns the shortest distance from `src` to `dst` in the weighted
directed graph `g`.
Graph.name: distance

doc: Returns the shortest distance between all pairs of nodes in the
weighted directed graph `g`. Returns `None` if `g` contains a
negative cycle.
Graph.name: distances

doc: Returns the shortest distance from `src` to every other node in the
weighted directed graph `g`.
Graph.name: distancesFrom

doc: Returns the graph where all edges in the directed graph `g` have their
nodes flipped.
Graph.name: flipEdges

doc: Returns a mapping from distances to the set of nodes for which the
shortest path from `src` in the directed graph `g` is of a given length.
Graph.name: frontiersFrom

doc: Returns the in-degree (how many edges end in a given node)
of each node in the directed graph `g`.
Graph.name: inDegrees

doc: Returns the inverse graph of the directed graph `g`. For all nodes in
`g`. The new graph contains exactly those edges that are not in `g`.
OBS: No self-edges are returned no matter the input.
Graph.name: invert

doc: Returns `true` if the directed graph `g` contains at least one cycle.
Graph.name: isCyclic

doc: Returns the out-degree (how many edges start in a given node)
of each node in the directed graph `g`.
Graph.name: outDegrees

doc: Returns `true` if there is a path from `src` to `dst` in the directed
graph `g`.
Graph.name: reachable

doc: Returns the nodes that are reachable from `src` in the directed
graph `g`.
Graph.name: reachableFrom

doc: Returns the strongly connected components of the directed graph `g`.
Two nodes are in the same component if and only if they can both
reach each other.
Graph.name: stronglyConnectedComponents

doc: Returns a Graphviz (DOT) string of the directed graph `g`.
The strings of nodes are put in quotes but DOT identifier validity is
up to the caller.
Graph.name: toGraphviz

doc: Returns a Graphviz (DOT) string of the directed graph `g`.
The strings of nodes are put in quotes and existing quotes are escaped.
Other than that, DOT identifier validity is up to the caller.
Graph.name: toGraphvizWeighted

doc: Returns a copy of the directed graph `g` where all flipped edges are
added. An undirected graph in directed representation.
Graph.name: toUndirected

doc: Returns a copy of the weighted directed graph `g` where all flipped
edges are added. An undirected graph in directed representation.
Graph.name: toUndirectedWeighted

doc: Returns the topologically sorted nodes (all edges go from lower indices
to higher indices of the list) in the directed graph `g`.
Unordered nodes are consistently (although not intuitively) ordered.
OBS: No cycles must be present.
Graph.name: topologicalSort

doc: Returns the nodes that are unreachable from `src` in the directed
graph `g`.
Graph.name: unreachableFrom

doc: Returns the nodes that are at most `limit` (inclusive) distance away
from `src` in the weighted directed graph `g`.
OBS: No negative cycles must be present.
Graph.name: withinDistanceOf

doc: Returns the nodes that are at most `limit` (inclusive) edges away
from `src` in the directed graph `g`.
Graph.name: withinEdgesOf

doc: Returns an iterator over lines from the standard input stream.
The iterator ends when the stream is closed or when an error occurs.
When the iterator is garbage collected the standard input stream is closed.
Thus, the `readLines` function should not be called more than once per program.
See also `Console.readLine` for reading from the console.
System.StdIn.name: readLines

doc: Apply every function from `f` to every argument from `l` and return a list with all results.
For `f = f1, f2, ...` and `l = x1, x2, ...` the results appear in the order
Whether the i-th function in `f` (`fi`) is applied eagerly or lazily depends on its purity:
- If `fi` is pure then it is applied lazily (i.e. the tail of `l` is not forced).
- If `fi` is impure then it is applied eagerly (i.e. the entire list `l` is forced).
Note that this implies that ALL functions in `f` must be pure to avoid forcing `l`.
DelayList.name: ap

doc: Returns `l2` appended to `l1`.
Does not force the tail of `l1`.
DelayList.name: append

doc: Returns the number of elements in `l` that satisfy the predicate `f`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: count

doc: Returns `l` without the first `n` elements.
Returns `ENil` if `n > length(l)`.
Returns `l` if `n < 1`.
Does not force the tail of `l`.
DelayList.name: drop

doc: Returns `l` without the longest prefix that satisfies the predicate `f`.
Whether `f` is applied eagerly or lazily depends on its purity:
- If `f` is pure then it is applied lazily (i.e. the tail is not forced).
- If `f` is impure then it is applied eagerly (i.e. the tail is forced until the first element that satisfies `f`).
DelayList.name: dropWhile

doc: Returns an empty DelayList.
DelayList.name: empty

doc: Returns an iterator over `l` zipped with the indices of the elements.
DelayList.name: enumerator

doc: Returns `true` if and only if at least one element in `l` satisfies the predicate `f`.
Returns `false` if `l` is empty.
Forces elements of `l` until the predicate `f` is satisfied.
DelayList.name: exists

doc: Returns a `DelayList` with every element in `l` that satisfies the predicate `f`.
Whether `f` is applied eagerly or lazily depends on its purity:
- If `f` is pure then it is applied lazily (i.e. the tail is not forced).
- If `f` is impure then it is applied eagerly (i.e. the entire list `l` is forced).
DelayList.name: filter

doc: Collects the results of applying the partial function `f` to every element in `l`.
Whether `f` is applied eagerly or lazily depends on its purity:
- If `f` is pure then it is applied lazily (i.e. the tail is not forced).
- If `f` is impure then it is applied eagerly (i.e. the entire list `l` is forced).
DelayList.name: filterMap

doc: Optionally returns the first element of `l` that satisfies the predicate `f` when searching from left to right.
Forces elements of `l` until the predicate `f` is satisfied.
DelayList.name: findLeft

doc: Returns the first non-None result of applying the partial function `f` to each element of `l`.
Returns `None` if every element `f(x)` of `l` is `None`.
Forces elements of `l` until `f(x)` returns `Some(v)`.
DelayList.name: findMap

doc: Optionally returns the first element of `l` that satisfies the predicate `f` when searching from right to left.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: findRight

doc: Returns the result of applying `f` to every element in `l` and concatenating the results.
Whether `f` is applied eagerly or lazily depends on its purity:
- If `f` is pure then it is applied lazily (i.e. the tail is not forced).
- If `f` is impure then it is applied eagerly (i.e. the entire list `l` is forced).
DelayList.name: flatMap

doc: Returns the concatenation of the elements in `l`.
Does not force the tail of `l`.
DelayList.name: flatten

doc: Applies `f` to a start value `s` and all elements in `l` going from left to right.
That is, the result is of the form: `f(...f(f(s, x1), x2)..., xn)`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: foldLeft

doc: Returns the result of mapping each element and combining the results.
DelayList.name: foldMap

doc: Applies `f` to a start value `s` and all elements in `l` going from right to left.
That is, the result is of the form: `f(x1, ...f(xn-1, f(xn, s))...)`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: foldRight

doc: Applies `f` to a start value `z` and all elements in `l` going from right to left.
That is, the result is of the form: `f(x1, ...f(xn-1, f(xn, z))...)`.
A `foldRightWithCont` allows early termination by not calling the continuation.
Calling the continuation forces the list `l`.
DelayList.name: foldRightWithCont

doc: Returns `true` if and only if all elements in `l` satisfy the predicate `f`.
Returns `true` if `l` is empty.
Forces elements in `l` until the first element that does not satisfy the predicate `f` (inclusive).
DelayList.name: forAll

doc: Applies `f` to every element of `l`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: forEach

doc: Applies `f` to every element of `l` along with that element's index.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: forEachWithIndex

doc: Returns an infinite sequence of integers starting from and including `n`.
DelayList.name: from

doc: Returns `Some(x)` if `x` is the first element of `l`.
Returns `None` if `l` is empty.
Does not force the tail of `l`.
DelayList.name: head

doc: Returns the concatenation of the elements in `l2` with the elements
of `l1` inserted between every two adjacent elements of `l2`.
Does not force the tail of `l2`.
DelayList.name: intercalate

doc: Returns `l` with `x` inserted between every two adjacent elements.
Does not force the tail of `l`.
DelayList.name: intersperse

doc: Returns true if and only if `l` is the empty DelayList, i.e. `ENil`.
Does not force the tail of `l`.
DelayList.name: isEmpty

doc: Returns `l` as an `Iterator`.
Does not force any elements of the list.
DelayList.name: iterator

doc: Returns the concatenation of the string representation
of each element in `l` with `sep` inserted between each element.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: join

doc: Returns the concatenation of the string representation
of each element in `l` according to `f` with `sep` inserted between each element.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: joinWith

doc: Returns `Some(x)` if `x` is the last element of `l`.
Returns `None` if `l` is empty.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: last

doc: Returns the length of `l`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: length

doc: Returns the result of applying `f` to every element in `l`.
Whether `f` is applied eagerly or lazily depends on its purity:
- If `f` is pure then it is applied lazily (i.e. the tail is not forced).
- If `f` is impure then it is applied eagerly (i.e. the entire list `l` is forced).
DelayList.name: map

doc: Returns the result of applying `f` to every element in `l` along with that element's index.
That is, the result is of the form: `f(x1, 0) :: f(x2, 1) :: ...`.
Whether `f` is applied eagerly or lazily depends on its purity:
- If `f` is pure then it is applied lazily (i.e. the tail is not forced).
- If `f` is impure then it is applied eagerly (i.e. the entire list `l` is forced).
DelayList.name: mapWithIndex

doc: Optionally finds the largest element of `l` according to the `Order` on `a`.
Returns `None` if `l` is empty.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: maximum

doc: Optionally finds the largest element of `l` according to the given comparator `cmp`.
Returns `None` if `l` is empty.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: maximumBy

doc: Returns `true` if and only if `l` contains the element `x`.
Forces elements until `x` is found.
DelayList.name: memberOf

doc: Optionally finds the smallest element of `l` according to the `Order` on `a`.
Returns `None` if `l` is empty.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: minimum

doc: Optionally finds the smallest element of `l` according to the given comparator `cmp`.
Returns `None` if `l` is empty.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: minimumBy

doc: Returns a pair of lists `(l1, l2)` where:
- `l1` contains all elements of `l` that satisfy the predicate `f`.
- `l2` contains all elements of `l` that DO NOT satisfy the predicate `f`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: partition

doc: Returns a `DelayList` of all integers between `b` (inclusive) and `e` (exclusive).
Returns an empty `DelayList` if `b >= e`.
DelayList.name: range

doc: Applies `f` to all elements in `l` going from left to right until a single value `v` is obtained.  Returns `Some(v)`.
That is, the result is of the form: `Some(f(...f(f(x1, x2), x3)..., xn))`
Returns `None` if `l` is empty.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: reduceLeft

doc: Applies `f` to all elements in `l` going from right to left until a single value `v` is obtained.  Returns `Some(v)`.
That is, the result is of the form: `Some(f(x1, ...f(xn-2, f(xn-1, xn))...))`
Returns `None` if `l` is empty.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: reduceRight

doc: Returns an infinite DelayList of repeating `x`s.
DelayList.name: repeat

doc: Returns `l` with every occurrence of `from` replaced by `to`.
Does not force the tail of `l`.
DelayList.name: replace

doc: Reverses the list `l`.
Does not force the tail of `l`.
DelayList.name: reverse

doc: Returns the result of running all the actions in the DelayList `l`.
DelayList.name: sequence

doc: Shuffles `l` using the Fisher–Yates shuffle.
DelayList.name: shuffle

doc: Return the singleton list with element `x`.
DelayList.name: singleton

doc: Returns a pair of lists `(l1, l2)` where:
- `l1` is the longest prefix of `l` that satisfies the predicate `f`.
- `l2` is the remainder of `l`.
Whether `f` is applied eagerly or lazily depends on its purity:
- If `f` is pure then it is applied lazily (i.e. the tail is not forced).
- If `f` is impure then it is applied eagerly (i.e. the entire list `l` is forced).
DelayList.name: span

doc: Returns the sum of all elements in the DelayList `l`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: sum

doc: Returns the sum of all elements in the DelayList `l` according to the function `f`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: sumWith

doc: Returns `l` without the first element.
Does not force the tail of `l`.
DelayList.name: tail

doc: Returns the first `n` elements of `l`.
Does not force the tail of `l`.
DelayList.name: take

doc: Returns the longest prefix of `l` that satisfies the predicate `f`.
Whether `f` is applied eagerly or lazily depends on its purity:
- If `f` is pure then it is applied lazily (i.e. the tail is not forced).
- If `f` is impure then it is applied eagerly (i.e. the tail is forced until the first element that satisfies `f`).
DelayList.name: takeWhile

doc: Returns `l` as an `Array`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: toArray

doc: Returns `l` as a `List`.
Forces the entire list `l`.
DelayList.name: toList

doc: Returns the association list `l` as a map.
If `l` contains multiple mappings with the same key, `toMap` does not
